<div id="review_3485249721" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3485249721" />
    <a title="Prem Sylvester" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21751173-prem-sylvester"><img alt="Prem Sylvester" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1623178248p2/21751173.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3485249721?book_show_action=true">Aug 08, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Prem Sylvester" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Prem Sylvester" href="/user/show/21751173-prem-sylvester">Prem Sylvester</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3485249721" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12187616447855162253">This was quite a strange read - structurally, it reminded me of Calvino&apos;s If On Winter&apos;s Night a Traveler. But where the latter had more fun with the narrative, this is much darker. It is a speculation on consciousness, on the overlap of dreamworlds with our waking dreams. The implications are intelligently hinted at, and well-drawn.<br/>A lot of the story threads - especially in the &apos;dream&apos; sequences - however, don&apos;t tie into each other until late into the book, so the seeming incoherence of the plo</span>
  <span id="freeText12187616447855162253" style="display:none">This was quite a strange read - structurally, it reminded me of Calvino's If On Winter's Night a Traveler. But where the latter had more fun with the narrative, this is much darker. It is a speculation on consciousness, on the overlap of dreamworlds with our waking dreams. The implications are intelligently hinted at, and well-drawn.<br />A lot of the story threads - especially in the 'dream' sequences - however, don't tie into each other until late into the book, so the seeming incoherence of the plot early on can be a little frustrating. But trust Banks - the payoff is quite rewarding. It helps that at the heart of this book is a rather tending and moving love story. The question at the crux of all the stories herein is simply, then - what dreams are worth waking up from?</span>
  <a data-text-id="12187616447855162253" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review3485249721">
  <td colspan="2">
    <div class="updateActionLinks">
